commits.commitMessage:
Fix an atClient crash which results in failed AV bootstrap

Remove redundant le_atClient_Create and le_atClient_SetDevice calls as they are covered by the le_atClient_SetCommandAndSend.

Resolves: LE-16544
Change-Id: I2e397036cd8898472f02839c9289925de410d327
commits.subject: Fix an atClient crash which results in failed AV bootstrap

comments.message: Can you clarify why le_atClient_Stop() shouldn't always be called to clean up?  I would naively expect the number of calls to le_atClient_Start() and le_atClient_Stop to need to be balanced -- which it is in the original code.

I only changed it because my investigation of le_atClient_SetCommandAndSend shows that it does the cleanup internally without the need to calling le_atClient_Stop in the case it fails. 

Calling le_atClient_Stop when it cleanup has occured due to an error from le_atClient_SetCommandAndSend will also return LE_FAULT now because of the fix.

Looks like le_atClient_SetCommandAndSend() does it's own internal le_atClient_Create(); and so le_atClient_Create() should NOT be called first.  Naming is maybe bad -- sounds more like le_atClient_CreateCommandAndSend().
cmdRef is an _OUT_ parameter of le_atClient_SetCommandAndSend().  Not an IN/OUT parameter -- should not be creating a command ref above.

commits.commitMessage:
Enable PS switch State update in GSM mode

- Report PS Switch State update event to PSStateEventId.

- Send CREG or CEREG notification in MRC init depending on device
  RAT configuration in PA, rather than in compilation time. Thus,
  macro LTE_ONLY_TARGET macro no longer needed.

Resolves: LE-16180
Change-Id: I83fed33f9a402d2df0e51267eda2619d46fed7e8
commits.subject: Enable PS switch State update in GSM mode

comments.message: Can you please confirm if the second state for tracking the GSM explicitly is required?   I thought +CREG URC is reported for both LTE and GSM.

As we discussed in meeting, only registering +CREG URC might be working, but I think we'd better to confirm with FW team. Sam, do you know who's the best person in your team we can consult about this (to get us noticed if there's PS switch state update in LTE and GSM modes)?
Hi Vincent, I've added a comment to your thread regarding the necessity to check CREG/CEREG. Hope this clears it up for you.

Hi Vincent, regarding the CEREG/CREG situation, in accordance with the 3GPP spec

"If the EPS MT in GERAN/UTRAN/E-UTRAN also supports circuit mode services and/or GPRS services,
the +CREG command and +CREG: result codes and/or the +CGREG command and +CGREG: result
codes apply to the registration status and location information for those services."

Essentially CREG and CEREG are not obligated to report the same information. So in this case it is required for us to explicitly check the relevant URC: either CEREG in E-UTRAN or CREG status in GSM mode. Hopefully this clears up your question
Can this also use the new ReportPSState() function?
Shouldn't use AT+CREG=n for all RATs configuration

Hi Vincent, does this assume the module is either GSM only or LTE only? The modes are not mutually exclusive (hl7812 is both, for example)
In the case of HL7812/HL7802 build, does this code work as intended?

the macro LTE_ONLY_TARGET is kept here assuming there're other platforms other than HL (such as RaspPi) using this code, as this file is shared platform adapor. As for HL78, with this patchset, LTE_ONLY_TARGET is no longer #defined, that means AT+CREG is used here for both GSM and LTE. This was discussed with Lars and tested by both Lars and I and worked fine. That's why we will need your look at this if we missed something that will cause some issues.
As mentioned before, if the UE supports both then we should enable both. We cannot rely only on CREG if UE is operating in CATM or NBIOT mode
New patch uploaded with determining the RAT by AT%RATIMGSEL?
Don't think we really need the variable state.   Why not directly set statePtr instead?
I think it's OK here, statePtr is a pointer used twice to point the item from mem pool, if directly set it then we will still need another pointer.

commits.commitMessage:
Stop atClient when connecting to AVC

This patch stops the atClient when connecting to AVC. If the atClient is not stopped properly, it results in issues like error messages and missing characters in the AT port when echoing.

Resolves: LE-16229
Change-Id: I96534553bca291a90cc8e291f29340ccb10a8936
commits.subject: Stop atClient when connecting to AVC

commits.commitMessage:
Move setting edm polling timer into a PA layer

Move setting edm polling timer into their own respective PA layer. Not all platforms will use an AT cmd implementation.

Resolves: LE-16187
Change-Id: Ibb8a64f9b68f5fde199c1974bdd0f44e4b188611
commits.subject: Move setting edm polling timer into a PA layer

comments.message:
"LE_TIMOUT" should be "LE_TIMEOUT", and "occured" should be "occurred".

Besides, I don't think this function will return LE_TIMEOUT, because it tries to ignore such kind of error by converting the error code to LE_OK.
Why ignoring timeout and return LE_OK is reasonable here? Should I use the same logic in RC76?
I added that as an edge case that happens when using the AT adaptor and it's not supported. Don't think it applies to RC76 since it's QAPI based.

[LE-15446] AT+KCELL=0 does not return neighbour cells while RAT is 2G

commits.commitMessage:
Handle GSM network errors by default (+CMS ERROR:)

While testing with a gsm module that was not booked into a network,
the modemService was blocked on startup as +CMS errors were not handled.
Adding +CMS ERROR: to the patterns of possible return values fixes this.

Resolves: #2 LE-13357
Change-Id: I63fe9a33f1bee94ab835a8f64c40da1f3922c640
Signed-off-by: Bertrand Roussel <broussel@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: Handle GSM network errors by default (+CMS ERROR:)

To be consistent with the rest of this function, you may want to use:
if (lteOpMode != NULL)
lteOpMode is always LE_MRC_LTE_CIOT_NONE set as output of this function (i.e. when lteOpMode input is not NULL). Is this really the intention?
Yes, it is.  This is in le_pa_common.  The working PA interface is with QMI in the file le_pa/pa_mrc_qmi.c that will check with QMI and set this value accordingly.

commits.commitMessage:
Correct return value for AT API

Some AT API call le_atClient_GetFinalResponse and return
its return. This will be incorrect if GetFinalResponse
return LE_OK, but the response string is not "OK"

Re-ordered function description return values

Resolves: LE-12422
Change-Id: I4e7c40dc3df49fced1c69a7988d73e90fd6773b3
commits.subject: Correct return value for AT API

comments.message: Should this be "return res;" to stay consistent with other code?
I will update code as your suggestion
This hasn't been updated/incorporated yet.  Right?
Don't need this to stay consistent with the other code
You should still use if(res != LE_OK) else if (strcmp      ), I was talking about having 3 returns which were unnecessary, but it's okay lets revert back to what it was with the If and Else If.
Same as above, revert back to previous patch

Could you please make the same changes in the header files, i.e. pa_info.h, pa_mdc.h etc, for all functions where you've changed the documentation comments. 
So that the function declaration documented the same way as function definition.

The convention across all Legato code is that LE_OK goes firs, and LE_FAULT goes last in the list of return values.

 * @return LE_OK            The function succeeded.
...
 * @return LE_FAULT         The function failed.

Can you please make sure this is the case in all functions you've touched?

is this really null as profileIndex looks to be a uint32_t. Is the if statement below a check to make sure that profileIndex is 0 or was it meant to be for profileDataPtr? This is probably fine because it was this way previously but looks confusing to me.

Yeah I think you're correct about both scenarios, it only checks if it is 0. It seems like the the indices for 3GPP ranges from [1,16] and 3GPP2 from [101,107], but I'm not sure if this criteria is always ensured by other code. Likewise, I'm guessing the ptr itself was the intended check too.

Proposed changes: 
1. Retain the original checking if profileIndex == 0 in the meantime
2. Also include a check that the profileDataPtr is valid be

In general, when do we expect these specific implementations to be used?   Most of them are simply stubs, so I assume they are for cases where the behaviour is not supported and therefore we want to return failures.  Is that correct?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> In general, when do we expect these specific implementations to be used?   Most of them are simply stubs, so I assume they are for cases where the behaviour is not supported and therefore we want to return failures.  Is that correct?

Well they used to be stubs and they were in the le_pa_common component which is used by both altair and AT pa based devices(raspi). now that the other patch actually adds an implementation for these functions, they are not common between altair and AT any more so i moved the stubs from common to the le_pa which is only used by raspi.

commits.commitMessage:
Move some functions from le_pa_common to le_pa

Move the following functions from le_pa_common to le_pa because altair
pa now has a different implementation:

pa_sim_AddSimToolkitEventHandler
pa_sim_RemoveSimToolkitEventHandler
pa_sim_GetLastStkStatus
pa_sim_OpenLogicalChannel
pa_sim_CloseLogicalChannel
pa_sim_SendApdu
pa_sim_SendCommand

Resolves: LE-13481
Change-Id: Ic21d0ae9326349462f639d7542d8e85eded45440
commits.subject: Move some functions from le_pa_common to le_pa

Patch Set 2:

Is PSState actually being used any more?  Or can we get rid of it?

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> Is PSState actually being used any more?  Or can we get rid of it?

Actually to have data connection, the UE has to be registered on network and get PS attached.

So in DCS, especially on HL78 product branch, both network registration state and PS state are checked before to start a data session.

On master for WP76xx, only PS state is checked and PS handler is used to update the PS state, but in PA code, there is a conversion used based on network registration and PS state.

So it is better to check PS state before to start a session/ retry, otherwise, resulting in extra power consumption.

commits.commitMessage:
Replace strerror() and strerror_r() with LE_ERRNO_TXT()

strerror() and strerror_r() have different behaviour and different
prototypes depending on the system.  So replace these with a new
function LE_ERRNO_TXT() which will behave like strerror() but is
thread safe.

Resolves: LE-14026
Change-Id: Id046e2c491fa9e6e0cf22de27ae342f6b2f8809b
commits.subject: Replace strerror() and strerror_r() with LE_ERRNO_TXT()

New Legato API to terminate the registration (T9/T10)

Add a new API le_ecall_TerminateRegistration(). After ecall normally
ended by PSAP or le_ecall_End(), it's used to terminate registration
state before T9/T10 or NAD_DEREGISTRATION_TIME expired.

    #ifndef LE_CONFIG_POSIX

If you want to keep CUSTOMOS, it should be:

In this file LE_CONFIG_CUSTOM_OS is not used, so what do you refer to in your comment?
This #define needs to be updated to match change below.  I.e. #ifdef LE_CONFIG_POSIX

commits.commitMessage:
[eCall] Report system standard change to PA layer

Issue:
When system standard is changed using le_ecall_SetSystemStandard(),
PA layer is not informed and keep using the old system standard.
This causes inconsistency when configuring system standard. (e.g:
PSAP number, eCall timers, ...).

Fix:
Notify PA layer each time system standard changes through
le_ecall_SetSystemStandard() function.

Resolves: LE-10357
Relates: LEAR7M-351
Change-Id: Ia2692fcc267b3387213561f31139f0b35dde1be6
commits.subject: [eCall] Report system standard change to PA layer

commits.commitMessage:
Add API to retrieve last reset reason

Add pa_info_GetResetInformation() API

Resolves: LE-7146
Change-Id: Iea1121a4df88bccb2b4f25faf6716095e7522f1d
commits.subject: Add API to retrieve last reset reason

comments.message: I would switch the title and the explanation: "Add API to retrieve last reset reason" is much more explicit for a commit title.
What is the point of this declaration?
The point of this declaration is to be able to retrieve the reset info via at commands, so in case someone tries to use at pa it'll return LE_UNSUPPORTED

Yes but that's already what the symbol in pa_info_default.c

PAs should only contains the implementation of functions that they support, and not any stubs.
pa_info_default.c is there to provide the stubs for the ones that are not implemented.

This isn't a stub func. This would be the implementation of the at command that retrieves the reset information (see funcs at the start of this file).

I agree with on the fact that it's useless to add the same func as in pa_default but this one should and have to be implemented, that's why I left it here.

I saw in the tracker(LE-7146) comments that "at!nv?reset_info" returns the reset information but it's not working.
Well at this point it is a stub. It doesn't look like the AT implementation is going to be part of this change, so I don't see the purpose of this particular patch.

me neither but it's not the only func that is implemented this way pa_info_GetPlatformSerialNumber() returns LE_FAULT.
What is the issue of having the same func in 2 different files ?

If there is no declaration in this file we can know what PA function is supported or not per PA at build time (cf checkpa script). If you provide a function we don't really have any way to know that it's actually a stub at build time.

As for pa_info_GetPlatform..., I would like this function not to be there as well but it unfortunately is. I've been trying to fight the declaration of these stubs in the AT and Simu PA for functions that are not implemented but it's not really sinking in.
well let's remove it for now and add it when we have an at command that can retrieve the reset information.
